threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factors were that it has known exploits and it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, ARM aarch64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, with debug_info, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a sample of the Qilin (aka Agenda) ransomware, specifically tailored for Linux and VMware ESXi environments. It features automated discovery and termination of virtual machines using 'esxcli' and 'vim-cmd' to release file locks, followed by the deletion of all VM snapshots to prevent data recovery. The encryption logic utilizes ChaCha20 for file data and an embedded RSA-4096 public key for key management, implementing a 'stepskip' (partial encryption) routine for increased efficiency. It persists its ransom message by overwriting '/etc/motd' and provides a script-mode assume-yes flag ('-y'). Relevant IOCs include the hardcoded ransom note branding ('-- Qilin'), specific ESXi command templates for snapshot removal and VM killing, and an embedded RSA public key used for the encryption payload.
